adian political and educational policy. Weaving together the current debates on citizenship with contributions by leading independent thinkers in the field, Citizenship in Transformation argues persuasively that since conceptions of democratic citizenship are changing, so too should operational definitions of citizenship education. Focussing on four dynamic themes - conceptual foundations, institutional policies, social and cultural realities, and education - the contributors address two critical questions: What constitutes a 'good' citizen in today's liberal democracy? And, what social and educational policies are needed to sustain the lives of these citizens, while not impinging on liberal democratic principles? Bringing together a variety of perspectives from theoretical and conceptual foundations, this book will have broad implications for social and educational policies and institutions in Canada.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aCitizenshipxStudy and teachingzCanada. 0aCitizenshipxStudy and teaching. 0aCitizenshipzCanada. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Civics & Citizenship.2bisacsh1 aBattiste, Marie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBourgeault, Guy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBruno-Jofré, Rosa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDePass, Cecille, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGagnon, France, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHaig-Brown, Celia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHébert, Yvonne M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHébert, Yvonne, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMagsino, Romulo F., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/voc